betterquesting:10.desc:8:
Angel blocks are used for the quite niche purpose of building when there are no blocks around.

To use them you place them down forehead.
A hostile planet where the atmosphere itself tries to crushes and burns you both from heat and sulfuric acid rain that eats away at your armor.
Has Solar Radiation and requires tier 1 thermal
Requires Thermal tier 1 but no radiation or pressure

Mars has an atmosphere that while strong enough to block out solar radiation, is neither breathable nor warm. This means you'll need tier 1 thermal padding to survive here as well as the usual oxygen setup.
No Need for Thermal, Radiation or Pressure Protection

An imbuement altar is found in ruined libraries found throughout forest biomes and contain an imbuement table along with bookshelves which may contain books and scrolls.

The imbuement altar is used for three different purposes:

1. Restoring Ruined Spellbooks to gain a new spell

2. Imbuing Crystals to be used in crafting Lore Specifc Items

3. Imbuing Robes with spectral dust to align the robes with that Lore.

These altars start out in a ruined state and need to have recepticals placed on each of their 4 sides before they can be used. You operate a completed altar by placing the spectral dust in the recepticals by right clicking with them in hand and the item to receive them on the alter itself (also by right clicking.)

Cyclopes can be found throughout the world either freely roaming with sheep in tow or in huts on beaches. They are quite powerful in melee and are strongly advised to be taken out via range, if you hit their eye you will blind it making it extremely vulnerable.

The purpose of this guy is to be a threat as their drop isn't that good. Though you can use them to kill most mobs as they seem to be hostile to just about everything.

The process of making GMOs begins with cultivating bacteria in incubators. You start this by making growth medium and dissolving it in water in an incubator and then put the liquid growth medium into another incubator with wheat to make bacteria. From here you should be able to figure out how to make the other bacteria variants.

You also use bacteria mixed with sugar to make enzymes used in the next step.

Something to note is that if you have at least 1 mB of a bacteria in an incubator you can make more by feeding in growth medium. You can carry around liquids less than a bucket by making a pippette which is found in the Cool Tools tab.

Oh yeah I forgot to mention it takes power, all of the genetics machines take RF/MJ.

The Isolator is used for you to take random genes from bees and store them as sequences. You pump in ethanol, and place inside enzymes, blank sequences, and what you want the genes of in and with a good amount of power and a load of time it will output a random sequence.

These function like Eyes of Ender except but are for finding the dens of tier 4 or 5 dragons. Like eyes of ender they can break when being used so you should be careful to have a few on hand.


They do have an upside in that if you are too far away from a dragon den it will inform you and not use the eye.

Do note that there isn't one for lightning dragons, just hope you find one I guess.

Spectral dust is used for it you want to minmax your spellcasting via making lore specific items and armor. You get it by killing remnants which spawn from spawners found in structures found throughout the world.

Ostriches can be tamed and ridden for those that want the worst option. To tame an ostrich you feed a female one (they have brown/bronze necks) melon seeds and after a few minutes it will drop an egg. You then place the egg on the ground and wait for it to hatch, like most Mo'Creatures mobs you need to be nearby when it hatches for it to be tamed.

Once hatches you wait for it to grow up and you can place a saddle on it and a helmet for armor.
Ravens are a tameable mob found in Roofed Forest biomes

This item lets you enable respawning of pets when you sleep in a bed. You hit them with the gem and it will toggle respawning and say so above your hotbar. You can disable their respawning by hitting them again.

Note that this item doesn't get used up.

Bears come in 4 different flavors, Black, Grizzly, Polar, and Panda and each interact in slightly different ways.

Black and Grizzly bears act like spiders in that they are neutral in light and hostile in darkness. Polar are always hostile, and Pandas are passive, even when hit. 

Bears will also attack farm mobs like cows, sheep, pigs and the like.

You can tame them by giving baby bears fish (raw or cooked), pandas eat sugar cane instead. Once fully grown they can be bred with any meat, note that like any Mo'Creatures mob the pair needs to be seperate from others of their species or they won't breed.

You can also ride tamed bears with a saddle and can mount a chest giving 18 slots. Do note that bears are quite slow compared to other mounts.

Wolves have some buffs to them to make them more suvival and useful. The first is that you can equip them with armor to protect them, the second is that you can equip them with a chest with 6 slots meaning it is actually good to take them with you on adventures.

Make sure to look into the Etheric Gem otherwise you might bleed through dogs in some fights.
This block is a combined ladder and trapdoor, bascially a ladder with a lid on the side.
Make stuff require blocks to make
Make stuff require blocks to make, also use fluxed equivilent

The largest of Mars' two moons it has deposits of Uranium and Thorium in greater concentrations than on Mars. It has no atmosphere to breathe, dangerous levels of solar radiation and requires at least tier 1 thermal padding.

betterquesting:10.name:8: Last Last I am the Last

betterquesting:10.desc:8:
Aluminum Ore is found in the twilight forest and is primarily used as a material for Galacticraft for making spacecraft and other components and machines.

You can't refine this in a normal furncae instead having to use an induction furnace.
Use Scrapers to get organic matter from mobs, use syringes to get blood from yourself
Use this to analyze organic matter into cells

Turn 8 helixes into a plank plasmid, use this machine to load a gene into that plasmid, note that basic genes of that mob can be used to fill that mob's trait. (IE skeleton basic mob progresses infinity).
Refines blood, must be done after extracting and before inserting.
Injects gene from loaded plasmid into blood sample, purify that blood and you can inject that gene.
Talk About Eggs, Seeds, Saplings, and Embryos

betterquesting:10.name:8: Perfect for Killing Tiny Baby Men

betterquesting:10.desc:8: Found in Mars Dunegon Treasure Chest

betterquesting:10.name:8: When Tommy Comes Marching Home Again
WHAT KIND OF PLACE IS THIS!?!?

betterquesting:10.desc:8: The centrifuge is used to get items from combs and propoli.

The Apiary is how you will house bees until you are able to make Alvearies. There are bee houses but they are can neither accept frames nor can you crossbreed for new kinds of bees.

To get materials from bees you place a princess and drone into an apiary to which will breed to make a queen which follows the breed of the princess. The queen will produce combs over time until it dies which will result in new drones and princesses.

The three slots in the middle allow you to place frames which have effects on them based on which ones you put in.

But the real fun begins when you breed a drone and princess of different breeds, the queen will have the same stats as the princess but their offspring will inherit their mixed genes. Each of the offspring will have a active and dormant gene, the active is the one that effects the bees stats and breed, while the dormant is merely held until to potentially be carried onto offspring where it may become active.

You can think of this like a pennant square, if you have a bee with 2 of gene A and another with gene A and gene B there is a 50% of the offspring getting 2 of gene A, 25% of gene A and B, and 25% of 2 of gene B.

To the right hand side it will show you the climate which is important as some bees can only live in specific climates based on temperature and humidity.

The left hand side will show any problems the bee is having such as lacking flowers, it raining, it being an unsuitable climate, or it being night.

Note that for some bees when it says they need flowers it is not refering to flowers but potentially other things whether that be cactus, certain ores, or simply stone.

To farm bees you need to get bees. One way is to go steal them from villagers, but that won't get you nearly enough. Instead you'll need to find beehives throughout the world, once found you need to break them with the scoop. Before you scoop them you will want to right click on them with a bee smoker otherwise they will attack you, ignoring armor.

You'll probably want to make multiple scoops as they has low durability. While the smoker doesn't have durability.

Different biomes will give different bees which will want to live in biomes similar to their own. For example, desert bees will want to live in hot and dry biomes while meadows bees will want to live in temperate and mild biomes. But you can solve this with a habitat former.

There are also two special cases for getting bees. Valiant are a rare drop from breaking hives and Steadfast are found in dungeon chests.

So you may have noticed that some of the bees you princesses you have harvested say pristine while others say ignoble. Ignoble princesses will have a 2% chance to die off after around 100 uses while pristines will not die off.

This 2% chance can be modified by stuff such as frames or electrical stimulators and each modifier is multiplicative and is refered to as genetic decay. So if you have an impregnated frame (.4 modifier) and 50% increase decay from electron tubes in an electrical stimulator it will go like this.

.02*.4*1.5=.012

You get these decimals from dividing the % by 100 or moving it over 2 to the left. Meaning your 2% became 1.2% for each generation. So you will likely get 183 uses out of that princess if you keep it up like that which is a lot, certainly long enough for you to get a swarmer which gives infinite ignoble princesses.

So them being ignoble or pristine doesn't matter really unless you are really cheesing crossbreeding by repeatedly killing your princesses since mutations occur at death.

Also to be clear Pristine are not effected by genetic decay and will not die from that.
The analyzer is used to look at the genes of a bee, tree, or butterfly at the cost of a honey drop (or honeydew) to reveal them.

The primary use of the Thermionic Fabricator is to make electron tubes which are needed for crafting farms and also for customizing circuits. This works by melting glass in the left slot and powering it until it melts and then it can craft in the recipe put in the table. 

You will need to provide it with power to keep the temperature high and the glass liquid. Otherwise it will lower the temp and and drain any liquid glass.

These farms offer 3 advantages over single block farms.

First is that you can use these to farm fruit trees by setting them to be orchard mode.

Second is that you can mix and match what you want to farm, having 1 side be a tree farm while another is a crop farm.

Third is that they use more of the space they take up, not having the 9x9 hollow space between the farm block and actual farmland.

Below is a link to the wiki showing how to make the farm as you get a lot of options and it will be best to have visuals.


{Embed}TypeLink;https://ftb.fandom.com/wiki/Multifarm;150;30;Building Multiblock Farm{Embed}

And now is time to mention manual vs automatic for multiblock farms. With manual you will have to place down the dirt and crops where you want them whereas an automatic will do so automatically. The exception to this is an orchard where even in automatic you will need to plant them and lay down dirt.

You set what you farm and in what mode using a circuit board (use intricate) and electron tubes with a soldering iron. You right click a soldering iron to pull up its UI, you can then switch to either managed or manual farm and insert electron tubes in the 4 slots to determine what you farm. To figure out which electron tubes do what search "electron tube" in JEI and hold shift over them to see. 

Once you insert the 4 tubes you can put it in the farm where this is a greyed trace of a circuit and you are ready to go if you did all of the information in the steps.

P.S. you may have noticed that you can configure other things with a soldering iron, keep that in mind for those blocks.

The alveary provides you the ability to give your bees a proper enviroment for them to work in by meeting their climatory needs. You do this by putting these blocks in your alveary but not in the top row of alveary blocks.

The Alveary Fan allows you to move the temperature of an alveary down 1 for each powered fan.

The Alveary Heater allows you to move the temperature of an alveary up 1 for each powered heater.

The Alveary Hydroregulator allows you to raise or lower the humidity of the alveary 20% by using water or lava respectivly. You can use multiple of them but note that they have a slight effect on the temperature effecting it by 10%

The Alveary Lighting tricks bees into thinking it is daytime.

The Rain Shield will make them able to work in the rain.

Forestry offers singleblock farms which will farm materials when provided with dirt, water, power, and fertilizer. Each kind of farm comes in two variants of each farm: managed and manual. Managed farms will automatically place down blocks and harvest them when ready, manual will require you to place them down so managed are best of them. The farms will place blocks in a 3 thick square ring 4 blocks away from the farm block and 1 block below it.

Note that these farms take very little power so you can run multiple of them based off of a single stirling engine.

Below are the different variants and any quirks with them:

Arboretum:
Lets you place based on cardinal directions. If you put it fruit trees it just cuts them down, you'll need a multiblock farm for them.

Peat Bog:
Takes in Bog Earth and outputs Peat and dirt

Crop Farm:
Same as Arboretum

Shroom Farm:
Takes in Mycelium or Podzol then works same as arboretum farm, chopping them down when they grow up

Gourd Farm:
Same as the crop farm.

Netherwart:
Uses soulsand instead of dirt and doesn't need water

End Flower:
Uses endstone instead of dirt and doesn't need water, it also doesn't filter chorus flower back into input so you will need to do that.

This bee begins the Industrial line and is also used to begin other lines such as working towards getting materials from bees.

The comb you get from this line of bees will get you propolis which is used in a large variety of items and can also be turned into sticky resin for rubber.

Now you've reached the end of the Industrial and can get pollen which is used for a few things mosty notably is that it is needed in excess for an Alveary. 

You can also use it to get some quite valuable bees such as the refined bee which produces fuel and also begins the line for getting different bees which give metals.
This bee continues the Industrial line of bees.

This the first kind of bee that you will breed, before you lies a journey to have bees provide a vast amount of different materials, many you cannot automate without bees.

This quest line takes you on the journey to the alveary, an upgraded version of the Apiary which is multiblock and allows you a great degree of freedom with your bees.

When crossbreeding bees I suggest getting a princess and drone of each type that way you can always make more.

Now that you've reached cultivated you can start to make a variety of different bees. The most important of which are the Industrious and Imperial line which are needed to make alvearies and are used frequently for crossbreeding of other bees.

This begins the Imperial line of bees, while they aren't as used as often for crossbreeding they are still just as important for reaching the Alveary as the Industrious line. 

This line also gives you honeydew which can often be used in place of honey sometimes.
This is step 2 for the Imperial line, other than being a stepping stone they are just used to get metal bees once you get Industrious bees.
Now you've finished the Imperial line and can get Royal Jelly used extensivly in making Alvearies and also used in making Ambrosia which are pretty an in between for golden apples.

The Alveary is a customizable multiblock that is a 3x3x3 of alveary blocks with a 3x3 of wooden slabs on the top with a texture being shown on the top layer of the alveary blocks when completed.

At base the alveary has a bonus to your bee's production by what sets it apart are the blocks you can customize it with. There are a variety of blocks which you can place in the alveary to give different affects which are listed in quests after this.

Note that you can't replace the top row of alveary blocks or the mutliblock won't form but you can mix and match which wooden slabs you use.

These blocks when added to your alveary will induce some sort of effect.

The Alveary Frame Housing allows you to add 5 of the frames to each of these blocks.

The Alveary Swarmer will, when fed royal jelly, spawn swarmer hives around it which will spawn ignoble princesses of the same genes and breed as the queen in the alveary.

The Alveary Stabiliser will prevent bees from mutating into a new species.

The Electrical Stimulator is used to give different effects when given different electron tubes in a circuit when powered at the cost of genetic decay. Note that the production effect caps at 1000% apparently.

The Alveary Transmission will give power to all blocks in an alveary that need it meaning you only need 1 power input.

The Mutator will increase the chance of mutation when fed items soul sand, ender pearls, or eyes of ender. Note that having multiple mutators will not stack their effects.

The Escritoire is used to increase the mutation rate of crossbreeding a combination 2 different bees for 1 result. You do this by playing a matching minigame whose difficulty is based on the tier of bee and upon completion grants you the bonus to mutation for that combo and also some combs.

You start by placing the bee you want to investigate in the center question mark. Slots will be then filled with books and the higher tier the bee the more slots will be taken filled.

On the right there is a microscope with slots underneath which when fed drones and then clicked (doesn't matter breed) will reveal some of the books to be bees at the cost of the drones fed in. You click on them to match those of the same breed, if you click on a non-matching pair then it will reset making any drones fed in wasted. To restart you just take the center drone out and put it back in.

You also don't need to use hints and just guess but that is not advised for high tier bees as that may take a long time.

Once you've matched all of the bees you will get a paper and some combs based on the investigated bee. Right clicking with the paper will give you a bonus for the combo listed. For example it may say that Wintry and Forest will make Common, it gives you a bonus to getting Common from that specific combo.

Before you begin genetically modifying you need to get subjects which you can modify to your desires.

The Hatchery will provide you with bee Larvae over time. These are used to create genetically modified bees and can be automated.

The Alveary Sieve will make it so that when butterflies spawn or trees cross pollinate they will instead deposit in here. The purpose of this is so you can genetically alter them. You put a woven silk in the left most slot and it will accumulate your goods in the right slots. You can only automate it using computercraft.
When fully equipped this set of armor will give you immunity to any of the negative effects given by bees such as jungle bees poisoning you.

Once you've retrieved your sequence you will need to analyze it to figure out what genes it isolated. You put in the sequence and DNA dye and with some power and time it will reveal the gene carried on the sequence.

Forestry is a mod about using machines to automate your agriculture with machines and also using bees to acquire resources.

Most forestry machines work in that you set a recipe by placing the recipe of what you want to craft in it (it won't consume them) and then placing said items you craft it with in its internal inventory. It will then need power and potentially liquids put in it before it can work.

The carpenter will also often require you to place in item in the top slot for it to work.

You will probably want more than one of these, one for each fluid usually.

The sequencer is used to essentially download the genes onto your database. You put in the analyzed sequence and fluorescent dye and it will update your database and output a blank sequence. You may have guessed that this item takes a while to process.

Note that you don't need to have a database made yet.

The Database keeps a record of all genese that you can put through the sequencer and is also how you select which genes to implant into your subjects.

You do this by clicking on the gene in the database with an empty serum vial.

There are also serum arrays which are able to hold multiple genes, infact 1 of each trait allowing you to do them all at once.
The genepool is used to turn anything with traits into raw DNA used in the next step.

The polymeriser is used to load serum vials or arrays with raw DNA and polymerising bacteria needed for the next step, you can speed this up by putting in golden nuggets.

Note that filling arrays will require more DNA and bacteria than simple vials.

You use this to inject your serum into your subjects, it takes a long amount of power and time, some of the times given in NEI go up to 2 hours for a full serum array but that can be worth it once you get the max level traits.

And now at the end you need only to grow your GMOs by supplying them with growth medium in an incubator.

But now is not the time to rest, for you will want to do this for every bee you want. 

The trial never ends.

At this point you've completed both the Imperial and Industrious line and made an alveary and now you will probably want to look into making other bees. 

The purpose for making these bees is that doing so allows you to easily automate the production of various materials for free and infinitely though balanced by requiring some investment if you want them to go at a good pace.

You can get almost any material from bees oil, redstone, certus quartz, uranium, dyes, metals, but there is the rare exception such as nether stars. Because of this it I personally think one shouldn't use bees for §oeverything§o §o§rbut that's up to you.

Also note that some bees might require more special conditions such as requiring a certain biome or dimension. You can usually find this by scanning them in your analyzer and keep in mind that if a bee gives a certain resource then you will probably need that resource nearby for them to work.

You can cross breed not just bees but also trees. You do this by having bees around trees which will cross pollinate nearby trees causing some of the leaves to change texture which can be seen more easily with spectacles equipped on your head.

Do note that the speed of cross pollinating is based on the bees which have a stat for it making some better than others. You harvest the cross pollinated leaves by breaking them with a grafter.

There are 3 main purposes for going into arbory:

First is that you want the various woods to build with or the trees as decoration.

Second is for food, Pam's trees are nowhere near as good as forestry trees for giving food as they are bigger and have more leaves to grow from.

Third are the industrial products from the trees mostly being fruits or nuts. Nuts are used to make seed oil and do so in much greater quantities than regular seeds. Fruits can be turned into biomass more efficiently than water and are quite abundant.

Though note that if you wish to farm them for their fruits you will need to look into multifarms.

Butterflies are created from forestry trees and only serve the purpose of making them cross pollinate. You can of course use them for decoration and as bragging rights.

You collect them by right clicking on them with a scoop and can be released by dropping them on the ground while it isn't raining and wait a second or two.

It seems that which butterlfy you get depends on the biome but you'd have to look into that yourself.

The Habitat former lets you change the climate for apiaries/alvearies, you give them power for temperature as well as water to humidify and lava to dehumidify. This is meant to allow you to meet the climatory needs of your bees without having to have a setup in each area.

They overall don't take up much power, a single stirling engine is enough to power a few though they are very slow when you have them covering even a medium area so keep that in mind. 

Note that the range listed is radius, meaning that many blocks in each direction.

It can also take crushed ice in place of water but I don't know if it is better than water, I would think so though.

That's right we got a mail system! This can be used to not only send simple letters but to instantly send items to other people's mailboxes. Though this is mostly meant for mailing between distant players it is somewhat useful for doing funny stuff.

You do this by making a letter, you can type out a message and or attach items to the letter. Don't forget to address it by typing the username of the recipient at the top.

But here's the kicker, you must attach stamps to it, each stamp has a certain value to it that being the number with the n next to it (I don't know what the n stands for so don't ask me.) The stamps come in different values being 1, 2, 5, 10, 20, 50, 100. You must put enough value to it to pay the postman, it is 1 as the base value, and then 1 addition for each item.

So if you have a letter with a stack of items attached it needs 65 worth of stamps. Now the second kicker is that you can only put 4 stamps on each letter, not 4 different kinds, 4 total. So for that 65 you might attach a 50 a 10 and a 5 with one slot left.

Once you have attached written your letter, attached any items, addressed it, and stamped it you can then send it by right clicking on a mailbox. If the recipient has a mailbox it will then send it to their mailbox.

Keep in mind that mailboxes work like vanilla enderchests in that whats in them is tied to the player, not the actual box. So you can open any mailbox to get your mail and only your mail.
betterquesting:10.name:8: All you need is a black and white cat

betterquesting:10.desc:8: Make it use electrotine doped wafers for higher tier stuff, use photovolatic plates
Movement is instant when duct is full, I guess useful if endpoint cannot handle input like a steam engine receiving steam from boiler.

The trade station is used to put custom trades that people can buy from with a catalogue in any dimension.

When opening a trade station you will be prompted to name it which cannot be undone without breaking it so make sure you give it the best name §l§oever§o§r. What follows is how to use it:

The recieve section is what you want and the larger section to the right the stockpile of what you have gotten. The send section is what you are selling and the larger section to the right of that is the stockpile for selling. You determine the rate of selling/buying by placing the amount you want to buy/sell in their section. 

For example if you want to buy 4 saplings for 6 gold ingots you will put 4 saplings in the receiving section and 6 ingots in the sending section. You then place ingots as a stockpile to the right.

You will also need to supply it with stamps and paper, you can figure out where these go by shift-clicking them in. Note that stamps work the same as letters and since people can buy in bulk you will want to give a variety of stamps. Next is how buys interact with them:

You open your catalogue and look for one you wish to buy from and click use. You then open a letter and it will automatically be linked to that trade station, how many items you send will determine how many you receive based the ratio. For example: if you send 24 gold ingots in the previous trade you will receive 16 saplings. You will still have to apply stamps.
Draconium Dust can be found at any height level on Venus, you'll need to do some refining if you want turn it into Draconium.

The fermenter is used to turn liquids, plant matter, fertiziler/compost, and power into biomass and quite quickly too. These liquids can be either water, honey, or fruit juice with the latter 2 producing biomass more efficiently.

The still is primarily used to turn biomas into Ethanol using power, it does so very slowly but Ethanol provides a decent amount of power. Though if you intend to use ethanol as your main power you will want to try and get your biomass production to be as efficient as possible and use plenty of stills.

You make the first of these by dropping a redstone, charged certus quartz, and nether quartz in water and letting them sit for a second or so. You get 2 for each you of them drop and can do as many as you want at a time.
You can make these in the Energetic Infuser
So these inscribers are a lot better than normal ones

betterquesting:10.name:8: Putting the World in a Computer

betterquesting:10.desc:8:
A multiblock structure that connects 2 potentially distant network fragments together. Created by crafting 8 ME Quantum Ring and a ME Quantum Link Chamber and placing the ME Quantum Link Chamber in the center, and sourrounding it in the 8 ME Quantum Ring.

Each Quantum Network Bridge requires power to function. This power must be provided from the network fragment it is attached to until the bridge is linked; at which time power from either side will be available. However if power is lost, connectivity will fail and power will be drained from the side the bridge is on in attempt to restore connection.

When the Quantum Network Bridge is powered, the various blue lights on the sturucture will turn on and glow. The Quantum Network Bridge requires 400 RF/t.

To establish a link between 2 Quantum Network Bridges, you must create a pair of Quantum Entangled Singularity. One of each will be placed inside of a particular connection. Each Bridge may only connect to one other bridge.

You might consider renaming your Quantum Entangled Singularity to better identify the connection.
Checklist

    Are both sides of the Quantum Network Bridge powered? The lights turn on if they are.
    Are the matching pair of Quantum Entangled Singularity in each bridge?
    Are both sides chunk-loaded?
    Make sure you only have 1 controller, the other side of the bridge is still the same network.
    Power and network connectivty must connect to the 4 edges, not the corners.

Normally Pure Crystals are grown by dropping the seeds in water and waiting for a long time, you could speed it up with growth accelerators or use this which though expensive, is automatable.

You simply put the seeds in and import the pure crystals.

You can also speed this up with acceleration cards.

Also Pure Nether Quartz isn't required for any recipes, it is just if you want to save on nether quartz.

Cats taming in this pack is a mix of both modern and in 1.12, you can tame both Ocelots and Stray cats found in villages. You tame them by feeding them fish, but you cannot just spam them with the fish, you get near them and wait for them to come to you before you can tame them. You know it works when they have smoke particles.

Note that tamed Ocelots do not change texture.

Also make sure to not overfeed them as they bug out for some reason and will refuse to move or sit, you fix them by punching them, not even joking. Make sure you don't have any animals that will fight for you nearby or you might be down a cat.

Also you can dye their collar with dye like with dogs (this is a mod, not vanilla.)

You can find black cats at witch huts.

The Wireless Connector is a block added by AE2 Stuff. It acts as a short-distance quantum bridge that is able to transfer up to 32 channels and is able to directly connect to ME Cables. Only two Connectors can be connected to one another via a Wireless Setup Kit. The default AE/t cost can be calculated as AE/t = 10 + distance^2 This connection only needs to be provided on one side, though it will not work across dimensions.
Useful if you don't use bees

The Inhibitor Obelisk prevents teleportation both to and from its radius. This radius is determined by which capacitor is placed inside it, below are the listed radius:

Basic Capacitor:              32
Double Layered Capacitor: 48
Octadic Capacitor:            80
This item will light up when you are over a slime chunk

These will act as free standing ladders that when placed on a block will place down until there is a block in the way or you use up all of the ladders in your inventory. They work like you should think they work.

This block is functionally identical to the Vanilla Button, though it is much larger visually, and adds a couple of unique features. Sneak+right clicking on the Big Button by an empty hand will open its inventory. It has an inventory of one slot, and putting items in it will increase the tick delay. 

Every item put into it will add 1 tick to the delay. There is a maximum of 64 ticks (3.2 seconds) delay for the Big Button; adding any more items will not add more tick delay, and is also likely impossible due to standardized stack sizes.
Don't ask me why graphite came after nanotubes.

Botany is a mod about breeding flowers and using said flowers to make pigments used for ceramic blocks. You start this by using a trowel on an area of grass and placing a flower or two down on the soil. If you place down a flower of a single kind (like just poppies) it will spread to empty soil, but if you place different flowers near each other they will cross pollinate, note that they don't need to have a space between them, just a space nearby.

When flowers cross pollinate the most common result is that they will exchange visual traits such as changing the color of the stem or flower which can get you a new color of pigment. But you can also sometimes get a new kind of flower.

Be aware that leaving empty soil around can spawn weeds, these weeds won't kill your flowers they spread and eventually die, overall they are pretty harmless.

Also note that flowers will die overtime but by that point will have probably spread to make more of them.

Also not all flowers can grow in certain areas and soil from different places have different properties. You can find info on them more in the quest above this one. I recomend just starting out in a plains or forest at around sea level.

So Botany added Electron Tubes which are used to configure circuits used to automate flowers in the Foresty Multiblock farm. I haven't tried them yet and not even the people who made GT:NH know if they even work but I have this here so you know about them if you want to test them out.

It seems like their purpose is to ensure the soil is exactly how you want it to be for your picky flowers and maybe auto harvest them but like I said I haven't tried them yet.

Ceres is not a planet but is instead the largest asteroid in the solar system with it making up a large percentage by mass of all asteroids in the belt.

It has no breathable atmosphere (shocking I know), requires tier 2 thermal padding, and will require protection against solar radiation.

On the plus side you can find Meteroric Iron as an ore here as well as Dolomite which will be needed for further progression in space.

You can also find a dungeon here which grants you the liscence for your next tier of rocket.

Putting rats in a cage decorated with a Rat Breeding Lantern will breed them. Cages are also multiblock structures that can eb linked to each other with Rat Tubes.

Plague is an effect caused by Plague Rat bites that prevents you from regaining health. The plague rats can be found in dark enviroments like normal rats and will spread its plague to any non-tamed rat that it comes in contact with.

You can craft Herbs and Plague Stew or trade with the Plague Doctor to get cures.

If nearby, the Plague Doctor will cure your plague and will cure the plague rats.

Certain upgrades require configuration. Whitelist, Blacklist, and Miner must be configured by right clicking with them in hand.

Cheese production can be automated by setting up a Curdling Station with a rat set to deposit milk into it, either with the Bucket Upgrade or the Milkmaid Upgrade.

Bind your rat to a Cheese Staff to set where they can take and deposit items. You can also set the Rats Home to give them an area to wander around. 

Make sure your rat is set to Hunt, Harvest, Gather, or Transport Items to make use of the staff.

The Rat Flute can be used to command multiple rats at once.

Make your first Block of Cheese by filling a cauldron with a bucket of milk.

Tame a Rat by dropping Cheese made from a Block of Cheese near them. 10 Cheese is needed for the rat to no longer fear you and up to another 5 Cheese is needed to tame them.

Rats can be found in the dark and from Garbage.

Once tamed you can right click them to open their GUI.
